definition.value: Any structural anomaly of cardiomyocytes, which are terminally differentiated muscle cells in the heart that are interconnected end to end by gap junctions, which allows coordinated contraction of heart tissue.
Deterioration of cardiomyocyte characterized by abnormal features such as loss of myofilaments, occurrence of cellular sequestration, decreased mitochondrial sizes and cellular debris.
Nuclear or cytoplasmic aggregates of stainable substances within cardiomyocytes.
An anomaly of the structure of mitochondria within cardiomyocytes.
A structural anomaly of lysosomes, membrane-enclosed organelles that contain an array of enzymes capable of catabolizing proteins, nucleic acids, carbohydrates, and lipids.
An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the stomach.
An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the duodenum.
An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the jejunum.
An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the colon.
An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the rectum.
An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the uterus.
A type of transposition of the great arteries (TGA) in which aorta is in front of and primarily to the left of the pulmonary artery.

label.value: Calcified amorphous tumor of the heart

definition.value: A solid, raised, plateau-like (flat-topped) lesion greater than 1 cm in diameter that is characterized by hardening (sclerosis) of the affected skin area (related to collagen thickening).
A solid, raised, plateau-like (flat-topped) lesion greater than 1 cm in diameter and that has a yellow color.
A type of purpura in which the lesions are raised (and can therefore be appreciated upon palpation).
A purpuric lesion that is larger than 1 cm in diameter.
Purpura that is flat (non-palpable, not raised).
A hole (perforation) in the wall of the intestine.
A hole (perforation) in the wall of the small intestine.
Increased rigidity and reduced mobility of the tongue.
Reduced strength of the muscles that lift or otherwise move the foot at the ankle.
Any abnormality in the multiplication or reproduction of cells, which may result in the expansion of a cell population.
Any abnormality in the multiplication or reproduction of lymphocytes, which results in the expansion of a cell population.
Any abnormality in the multiplication or reproduction of T cells, which results in the expansion of a cell population.
Any abnormality in the multiplication or reproduction of B cells, which results in the expansion of a cell population.

label.value: Decreased lymphocyte proliferation in response to mitogen

definition.value: A decreased proliferative response of lymphocytes in vitro or in vivo, when stimulated with mitogens, such as phytohemagglutinin (PHA).

label.value: Decreased lymphocyte proliferation in response to anti-CD3

definition.value: A decreased proliferative response of lymphocytes in vitro or in vivo, when stimulated with an anti-CD3 antibody against the T-cell co-receptor, CD3.
Abnormal amount of a protein that is normally present on the cell surface of lymphocytes.
